ENTRY            D6504   20260203   20260508   20260508       D151
SUBENT        D6504001   20260203   20260508   20260508       D151
BIB                 12         25
TITLE      Experimental study of alpha-induced reactions on 113In
            for the astrophysical p process
AUTHOR     (D.Basak, T.Bar, L.K.Sahoo, S.Saha, J.Datta,
            S.Dasgupta, A.Roy, N.Kinoshita, C.Basu)
INSTITUTE  (3INDSAH,3INDVEC)
           (3INDIND) Homi Bhabha National Institute,
            Anushaktinagar, Mumbai
           (3INDIND) Aryabhatta Research Institute of
            Observational Sciences, Manora peak, Uttarakhand
           (2JPNJPN) Technology of Institute, Shimizu Corporation,
            3-4-17 Echujima, Koto-ku, Tokyo
REFERENCE  (J,PR/C,110,065807,2024)
FACILITY   (CYCLO,3INDVEC) K-130 cyclotron
DETECTOR   (HPGE)
METHOD     (ACTIV) Each target stack irradiated for 2.5 to 18 hrs.
MONITOR    (29-CU-0(A,X)31-GA-67,,SIG)
DECAY-MON  (31-GA-67,4697.MIN,DG,184.6,0.214)
ERR-ANALYS (ERR-T) Total uncertainty propagated from
           (ERR-2,0.4,10.) Peak area counts (0.4-10%)
           (ERR-3,6.,7.) Target thickness (6-7%)
           (ERR-4) Detector efficiency (~9%)
           (ERR-5) Decay parameters from literature (~5%)
           (ERR-6) Energy straggling of beam in the target (~1%)
STATUS     (APRVD) Proof-read by D.Basak (2026-02-09)
HISTORY    (20260201C) VT
ENDBIB              25
COMMON               3          3
ERR-4      ERR-5      ERR-6
PER-CENT   PER-CENT   PER-CENT
         9.         5.         1.
ENDCOMMON            3
ENDSUBENT           32
SUBENT        D6504002   20260203   20260508   20260508       D151
BIB                  5          8
REACTION   (49-IN-113(A,G)51-SB-117,,SIG)
DECAY-DATA (51-SB-117,168.0MIN,DG,158.6,0.859)
SAMPLE     (49-IN-113,ENR=0.937) 113In target with thickness
            60 to 85 ug/cm2 were prepared by vacuum evaporation
            onto 2.7 um thick, high-purity aluminum backings.
ERR-ANALYS  Above 15 MeV, an additional ~30% uncertainty is
            included due to limitations of activity ratio method.
